data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-related patterns that don't exist in ASP.NET Core:

| .NET Framework Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Return from the action method |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code | Remove entirely |

## Migrated ASP.NET Core Controller

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // ASP.NET Core uses action methods that return IActionResult,
    // not event handlers. The framework handles the HTTP response lifecycle.

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End — return a FileResult instead.
        // The framework writes headers and body for you.
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Return a redirect result — no Thread.Abort, no endResponse flag.
            // Code after this DOES execute, so you must return immediately.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch is removed entirely:
        // - ASP.NET Core never throws it
        // - OperationCanceledException is the modern equivalent if needed
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. `return` is mandatory after redirect.**
In .NET Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` aborted the thread so code after it never ran. In ASP.NET Core, `Redirect()` just creates a result object — execution continues. Forgetting `return` means the rest of the method still runs.

**2. `Response.End()` has no equivalent — just stop writing.**
Don't search for a replacement. Return a result (`File()`, `Content()`, `Ok()`) and let the framework end the response.

**3. Dead `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks hide bugs.**
If your catch block had cleanup logic (releasing locks, rolling back transactions), move it to a `finally` block before deleting the catch. In this code it was a no-op swallow, so it's safe to remove.

**4. Use `HttpContext.RequestAborted` for long-running work.**
If `GenerateReport()` is expensive, pass the cancellation token so the server can stop work when clients disconnect:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core binds HttpContext.RequestAborted automatically
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
    return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

**5. Null-safety on `User.Identity`.**
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` if no auth middleware ran. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or the `[Authorize]` attribute instead of manual checks.
